Complexity Overload: Decision Trees & Model Tuning

Cornerstone #2 - How the World Works

In this module, we'll introduce a new paradigm for representing the relationships and patterns in data: tree-based models.

The following Coding Section is a core part of this module. After watching the video above, please follow along inside your Companion Workbook. Try to implement each piece of code on your own. You will also find exercises at the end of your Companion Workbook, which are meant to be completed AFTER the coding section.

 

I. Decision Trees: A New Paradigm¶

In the previous modules, we've been looking at linear (or variations of linear) models, including the mean model (i.e. horizontal line), simple linear regression (i.e. sloped line), and polynomial linear regressions (i.e. curvy lines).

In this module, we'll be shifting gears and introducing a new paradigm of modeling: tree-based models. In fact, we'll be seeing what happens when you are able to crank model complexity way up.

 

First, let's import all of the libraries we'll need.¶

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

import seaborn as sns
sns.set_style('darkgrid')
 

For this module, we'll also need the DecisionTreeRegressor class from Scikit-Learn.

In [2]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor
 

Next, let's read in the dataset that we saved as a CSV from Module 1.¶

In [3]:
df = pd.read_csv('simulated_data.csv')

df.head()
Out[3]:

Next, let's paste in the fit_and_plot_model() helper function we already wrote in the previous module.¶

  • Since we've already done these steps and validated them multiple times, there's no need to waste brain power on them anymore!
  • Note that we won't be using the fit_and_plot_polynomial_model() function this module, but we will return to it in the next module. In the next module, we'll be "putting everything together" and showing you what the entire analysis looks like from start to finish, in addition to introducing the #1 way to validate your models.
In [4]:
def fit_and_plot_model(df, model):
    # Splits input features from target variable
    features = df.drop('y', axis=1)
    target = df.y
    
    # Fits the model
    model.fit(features, target)
    
    # Plots the dataset
    plt.scatter(df.x, df.y)
    
    # Overlays the predicted values for y
    plt.plot(df.x, model.predict(features), 'k--')
    
    # Returns fitted model
    return model
 

Intuitively, decision trees build a model by creating splits in the data to separate subsets of the data based on your target variable. This results in a branching nature that allows very complex relationships.

We won't go deep into the theory here, but let's see them in action and try to understand exactly what they're doing from a practical standpoint.

First, let's use our helper function, fit_and_plot_model(), to fit and plot an unconstrained decision tree.¶

  • An unconstrained decision tree is one that is allowed to grow its branches without limitation. By default, DecisionTreeRegressor() creates an instance of an unconstrained decision tree. As we'll see in just a moment, this leads to a major problem: overfitting.
In [6]:
# Unconstrained Decision Tree
model = fit_and_plot_model(df, DecisionTreeRegressor())
 
 

Very interesting... it seems like the model has perfectly "memorized" the training data. As you can see, the predicted values perfectly match the actual values from the dataset. Unfortunately, this is typically NOT a good thing. Remember, our dataset was created from a noisy sine function, so we don't actually want to memorize that noise! Instead, we want to learn the underlying pure sine wave relationship.

To confirm, let's display the total difference between actual yy values and the predicted y^y^ values.¶

  • This is a bit foreshadowing for the next module, but basically one of the most common ways to evaluate a model is to look at the difference between the values it predicts and the actual values. This quantity is called the prediction error.
  • Usually, lower error is better, but ONLY when you are evaluating the model on a new "unseen" dataset called a test set... A lower prediction error on the training dataset doesn't mean anything, as the model could simply be extremely overfit!
In [22]:
# Original values of y
actual_y = df.y

# Predicted values of y
predicted_y = model.predict(df.drop('y', axis=1))

# Total difference between actual and predicted values of y
np.sum( np.absolute( actual_y - predicted_y ) )
Out[22]:
0.0
 
  • As you can see, our total absolute prediction error was 0. Again, because this is not on an "unseen" test set, a prediction error of 0 is a cause for concern and NOT a cause for celebration. The model is most likely overfit to the training dataset, and we'll see exactly how to validate this in the next module.
  • Also, note that we took the sum of the absolute values of the differences in case some differences were negative and others were positive.
 

In summary, the unconstrained decision tree is overfit.¶

  • Because the decision tree was unconstrained, it was allowed to make as many splits as it wanted to.
  • As a result, it just made branches until each xx value was in its own leaf!

For example, let's look at the first 5 observations from our dataset:

In [23]:
df.head()
Out[23]:
  x y
0 0.000000 0.086260
1 0.063467 0.881165
2 0.126933 0.145261
3 0.190400 -0.252824
4 0.253866 -0.320448
 

Because the decision tree was unconstrained, it could keep making splits until it isolated each of those xx values into a single leaf. The final decision leaves may have looked like this:

  • If x<x< 0.063467, predict 0.086260
  • If 0.063467 ≤x<≤x< 0.126933, predict 0.881165
  • If 0.126933 ≤x<≤x< 0.1904005, predict 0.145261
  • If 0.190400 ≤x<≤x< 0.253866, predict -0.252824
  • Etc...

Again, it obviously fits our generated dataset very well (perfectly, in fact), but it has essentially completely learned the noise, instead of isolating the signal.

 

II. Understanding Tree Structure¶

So why did the unconstrained decision tree overfit the dataset? Well, it all comes down to the structure of a decision tree. Because a decision tree is based on creating splits / branches (instead of learning... say... a coefficient), it can theoretically have an infinite number of splits.

Practically, this means that an unconstrained decision tree will keep splitting until every single observation from the training set ends up in its own terminal leaf. And for decision trees, every single branch / split location is a model parameter, which is why decision trees are considered a complex type of model.

Let's peel back and explore the structure of our model.

First, we can visualize the tree with the graphviz library.¶

  • You might not have this library installed yet. Please check the additional resources for this module for installation instructions!
  • Note: If you have trouble installing the graphviz library due to your system specs and cannot find a solution online within a reasonable amount of time, then please don't get stuck here. Simply keep moving on. We won't actually be using the library again, so it's not critical to install it if it's going to be a huge pain.
In [5]:
# Exports the tree structure
from sklearn.tree import export_graphviz

# Allows us to render the diagram in Jupyter notebook
from graphviz import Source
 

Next, let's save the structure as a PNG file and display it here.¶

  • After running this code, you can find the PNG file saved in the same folder as this notebook. You can open that file and zoom in to see the tree more clearly.
In [35]:
from IPython.display import Image

def plot_and_save_decision_tree(model, out_filename):
    # Export tree structure and save to Source object
    graph = Source( export_graphviz(model, out_file=None) )

    # Pipe to PNG bytes
    tree_png = graph.pipe(format='png')

    # Write to PNG file
    with open(out_filename,'wb') as f:
        f.write(tree_png)

    # Display image
    return Image(tree_png)
In [36]:
plot_and_save_decision_tree(model, 'tree_graph.png')
Out[36]:
 

As you can see, by allowing this tree to grow in an unconstrained way, we ended up with a pretty huge tree. But to really drive home this point, let's display some information about our model parameters.

First, we can display the node count, which is the number of branch locations + leaves.¶

  • In the diagram above, each rectangular box is considered a "node." The ones that don't further branch to any other nodes below them are considered "leaves."
  • These nodes are the model parameters for our decision tree, and they fully define the tree the same way the intercept and coefficients fully defined our linear models.
In [23]:
# Node count
model.tree_.node_count
Out[23]:
199
 

As you can see, for our model, we have 199 nodes. However, perhaps what's more useful to check is the number of leaves (or terminal nodes) in the model. Each leaf will have an actual prediction.

And since we only had 100 observations in our simulated noisy sine dataset, if we end up having close to or equal to 100 leaves in the model, then we can confirm from a structural standpoint that the model is indeed overfit. 100 leaves would mean each training observation ended up it is own leaf.

To confirm, we can look at either of two properties: children_left or children_right.¶

  • For each node, children_left and children_right show which other nodes it branches off to (if any).
  • If a node does not branch to any other nodes, it will have the value -1. This indicates that the node is a leaf.
In [24]:

Great, we've just confirmed based on results, a quick visualization, AND looking at the underlying structure that our decision tree is most likely overfit. So is that it? Should we just completely scrap the idea of using decision trees?

As it turns out, there are a few techniques we can use to take advantage of the flexibility and complexity of decision trees while safeguarding against overfitting. We will explore these techniques much more throughout the rest of the cornerstone projects in this program, but let's introduce them first.

 

III. Constrained Decision Trees¶

The first solution to overfitting decision trees is to constrain the decision trees. Remember, the reason the unconstrained decision tree becomes overfit is because it's allowed to keep branching willy nilly until it ends up with one leaf per observation.

There are different ways to constrain a decision tree...

The first common way is to constrain the maximum depth allowed for the tree.¶

  • In other words, we can constrain the maximum number of levels the tree is allowed to branch down. So if we set a max depth of 3, it means the tree is only allowed to branch down 3 times before it MUST arrive at a prediction.
In [28]:
# Depth-Constrained Decision Tree
model2 = fit_and_plot_model(df, DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth = 3))
 
 
  • Wow! The difference appears to be night and day. Whereas the unconstrained decision tree was completely overfit, the constrained decision tree by depth appears to approximate the sine wave fairly well.
  • Also, the above chart shows the branching nature of the tree much more apparently. Notice how the predictions appear to follow a step-like pattern instead of the smooth curvy pattern from the polynomial regressions.

Next, let's display the actual tree structure.¶

  • As you can see, the maximum depth is 3.
In [37]:
plot_and_save_decision_tree(model2, 'tree_graph_2.png')
Out[37]:
 

Another common way to constrain decision trees is to set a mininum number of samples that each leaf must have.¶

  • This will guarantee a mininum number of observations in each terminal node and avoid the situation where each leaf only has one observation.
In [62]:
# Leaf-Size-Constrained Decision Tree
model3 = fit_and_plot_model(df, DecisionTreeRegressor(min_samples_leaf = 5))
 
 

Next, let's display the actual tree structure.¶

  • As you can see, each leaf will have at least 5 samples.
  • Notice how this tree is constrained in a fundamentally different way than the depth-constrained one. This tree is allowed to have as many branches as needed as long as each leaf still has at least 5 samples.
In [63]:
plot_and_save_decision_tree(model3, 'tree_graph_3.png')
Out[63]:
 

Now the million dollar question is: how in the world should you choose these "structural settings" (i.e. maximum depth or minimum leaf size)?¶

  • As you might have noticed, we needed to set these structural settings BEFORE fitting the model. That means the algorithm did not learn this directly from the data. Therefore, these are called hyperparameters instead of standard model parameters.
  • The process of selecting the optimal hyperparameters is called tuning, and it's integral to applied machine learning. We'll explore this process in the next cornerstone project.
 

IV. Random Forests¶

The second solution to overfitting decision trees is to ensemble the decision trees. This is the process of combining predictions from many constrained decision trees.

In general tree ensembles perform very well in practice, and they tend to perform well across many types of problems. We'll cover them in much more detail later in the program, but here's a quick preview.

First, we'll need to import another class from Scikit-Learn called RandomForestRegressor.¶

  • Random forests train multiple decision trees in parallel and then combines their predictions into a single decision tree.
  • Each individual decision tree within the forest is only trained on a randomly selected subset of observations. In practice, this has the effect of "smoothing out" their predictions and safeguarding against overfitting.
In [41]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
 

One note is that we need to set a random state (i.e. a random seed) for the algorithm in order to obtain replicable results. Again, it's because random forests train each tree on a randomly selected subset of observations.

In [55]:
# Fit "unconstrained" random forest
rf = fit_and_plot_model(df, RandomForestRegressor(random_state=123))
 
 

As you can see, this has the effect of smoothing out the predictions in relation to a default unconstrained decision tree.

By default, it will fit 10 decision trees. We can actually view each individual tree!¶

In [64]:
# Number of decision trees in the random forest
print( len(rf.estimators_)  )

# Display first decision tree
print( rf.estimators_[0]  )
 
10
DecisionTreeRegressor(criterion='mse', max_depth=None, max_features='auto',
           max_leaf_nodes=None, min_impurity_decrease=0.0,
           min_impurity_split=None, min_samples_leaf=1,
           min_samples_split=2, min_weight_fraction_leaf=0.0,
           presort=False, random_state=843828734, splitter='best')
 

Here's what that first tree looks like.¶

In [58]:
plot_and_save_decision_tree(rf.estimators_[0], 'rf_tree_0.png')
Out[58]:
 

As you might guess, we can actually constrain random forests as well. For example, we can set a mininum leaf size for EACH individual tree in the forest.¶

  • Again, notice how the random forest "smooths out" the predictions compared to a single decision tree constrained the same way. This is a result of combining predictions from 10 different trees that are each trained on partial data.
In [59]:
# Random forest with trees constrained by leaf size
constrained_rf = fit_and_plot_model(df, RandomForestRegressor(min_samples_leaf=5,
                                                              random_state=123))
 
 

Next, let's display a single tree from the random forest. Notice how each leaf has a mininum sample size of 5.¶

  • This also has the practical effect of making each tree much smaller compared to the trees in the unconstrained random forest.
In [60]:
plot_and_save_decision_tree(constrained_rf.estimators_[0], 'constrained_rf_tree_0.png')
Out[60]:
 

Finally, let's display another tree from the constrained random forest.¶

  • Notice how its structure is different from the one above. At the risk of beating a dead horse... this is due to each tree being trained on partial data.
  • In practice, random forests will be among our most used algorithms. They have many great properties, and they perform very well as a general-purpose machine learning algorithm. We'll explore them in more detail later in the program.
In [61]:
plot_and_save_decision_tree(constrained_rf.estimators_[1], 'constrained_rf_tree_1.png')
Out[61]:
 

Random forests also have hyperparameters to tune, including the number of trees to include in the forest and whether to constrain each tree. We'll explore this process in the next cornerstone project. However, one of the benefits to random forests is that they tend to perform quite well "out-of-the-box," even beating other models that take days to tinker with and train. For that reason, many data scientists like to use them as a reliable baseline model
